properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow will develop this evening over the lower St. Lawrence and the Gaspe Peninsula, and will reach the North Shore on Tuesday morning. Snowfall totals of 20 to 40 centimetres over the Lower St. Lawrence and the Gaspe Peninsula and of 15 to 25 centimetres over the Lower North Shore are expected by Wednesday afternoon. This snow will be accompanied by strong winds giving locally poor visibilities in blowing snow. Snow will change over to rain overnight Tuesday night over the Chevery and Blanc-Sablon areas. A few hours of freezing rain are possible during the changeover from snow to rain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall expected Tuesday night and Wednesday. Total Rainfall: possibly reaching 50 mm. Location: along the coast from Bay St. George to Gros Morne and as far inland as Deer Lake. Time Span: Tuesday afternoon or evening until Wednesday afternoon. Remarks: Snow will begin Tuesday morning and give 5 to 10 cm before transitioning to rain by late Tuesday afternoon or early evening. The highest rainfall totals will most likely fall over higher elevations where up to 50 mm is possible. Rain and warm temperatures will combine to cause any existing snow pack to melt and may contribute to water pooling. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:

Description: Significant snowfall today into tonight. Snow will become heavy at times this afternoon and continue tonight. Snowfall amounts of 15 cm are likely by tonight. Travel will be impacted today due to accumulating snow as well as locally reduced visibility in snow. This snowfall is due to a developing low pressure system which will track south of the lower Great Lakes today. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow Squalls are possible on Tuesday. In the wake of a cold front, a blast of cold arctic air is expected to flow over the relatively warm waters of Lake Huron Tuesday morning. Flurries and local snow squalls are expected to begin Tuesday morning and continue through the day in the Sarnia to Kettle point areas. Local snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm with local blowing snow reducing visibilities to near zero are possible. Local snow squalls are expected to taper off when the wind shifts to northwest Tuesday evening. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. Strong outflow winds continue to drive modified arctic air through mainland valleys as a frontal system crosses the region today. The combination of warm air from the approaching system overriding the cold outflow is producing freezing rain in valleys throughout the region. Freezing rain will persist until Tuesday morning when the outflow weakens and temperatures rise above zero. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Ice build-up may cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Approaching storm to bring snow, ice pellets, freezing rain and rain to the province tonight and Tuesday. The precipitation will start as snow tonight and then transition to rain along the Fundy Coast overnight and over eastern New Brunswick on Tuesday morning. 5 to 10 cm of snow is expected, and will be followed by a period of freezing rain and ice pellets over eastern New Brunswick before the changeover to rain. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions in the snow and mixed precipitation. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Approaching storm will bring significant rainfall Tuesday and Tuesday night. Rain will begin late tonight or early Tuesday morning across much of Nova Scotia and will continue, heavy at times, into Tuesday night. Total rainfall accumulations are expected to be quite variable, with forecast amounts ranging from 30 to 65 mm and locally higher amounts possible along parts of the Atlantic coast. Rain will change to flurries over western Nova Scotia late Tuesday night as cold westerly winds move into the region and temperatures quickly fall below freezing. Driving conditions may become icy overnight or Wednesday morning as the cold air and flurries push eastward across the province. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Approaching storm will give mixed precipitation Tuesday into Wednesday morning. Snow is forecast to begin over the Island early Tuesday morning and then change to rain before noon. The rain is expected to become intermittent on Tuesday afternoon, then redevelop on Tuesday night and continue into Wednesday morning. Total accumulations of 20 to 30 millimetres are currently indicated, but may increase in future forecasts if the track or intensity of the system change. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions in snow and mixed precipitation on Tuesday morning. Additional information will be provided as the details become more certain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A snowstorm is expected. Snow will develop this evening over the lower St. Lawrence and the Gaspe Peninsula, and will reach the North Shore on Tuesday morning. Snowfall totals of 20 to 40 centimetres over the Lower St. Lawrence and the Gaspe Peninsula and of 15 to 25 centimetres over the Lower North Shore are expected by Wednesday afternoon. This snow will be accompanied by strong winds giving reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Snow will change over to rain overnight Tuesday night over the Chevery and Blanc-Sablon areas. A few hours of freezing rain are possible during the changeover from snow to rain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. Snow will begin this afternoon over Southern Quebec. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Approaching storm to bring snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain to northwestern New Brunswick tonight and Tuesday. Snow will begin late this evening over northwestern New Brunswick and become heavy at times overnight and Tuesday. The snow is forecast to become mixed with ice pellets or freezing rain over portions of these regions except for Madawaska County and Restigouche County, where precipitation is expected to remain as snow throughout the event. Precipitation is forecast to taper to scattered flurries Tuesday evening. Total snowfall amounts of 20 to 45 cm are expected. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
